<div class="pil-intro"><div>
<h2 style="color:var(--accent-color);font-family:'Oswald',sans-serif;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:.06em">Purpose</h2>
<p>Data brokers compile profiles on virtually every American. Advertisers broadcast those profiles to hundreds of companies in milliseconds. Platforms engineer psychological dependency through dark patterns and engagement optimization. Companies use behavioral data to charge individuals the maximum they will pay. This pillar establishes that personal data is not a commodity, behavioral surveillance is not consent, and manipulation of psychological architecture is not marketing.</p>
</div><div>
<h2 style="color:var(--accent-color);font-family:'Oswald',sans-serif;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:.06em">Core Principle</h2>
<p><strong>You own your data.</strong> Companies that collect it are stewards under strict legal constraint, not owners with rights to sell, profile, and exploit. The burden is on the collector to justify every use, not on you to escape every extraction.</p>
</div></div>
</div>
</section>
<section class="bg-dark on-dark ruled" id="pil-problem">
<div class="wrap" style="margin-bottom:0"><h2 style="color:var(--accent-color)">The Problem It Solves</h2></div>
<div class="wrap"><ul>
<li>The U.S. has no comprehensive federal data privacy law. The $200-260 billion data broker industry operates with no federal registration requirement, no mandatory deletion mechanism, and no prohibition on selling the most sensitive categories of personal data.<sup><a href="#fn1" id="ref1" style="text-decoration:none">[1]</a></sup></li>
<li>Reading every privacy policy you encounter would take 76 work days per year, making notice-and-choice frameworks mathematically incapable of providing meaningful consent.<sup><a href="#fn2" id="ref2" style="text-decoration:none">[2]</a></sup></li>
<li>The average American's behavioral profile is broadcast to hundreds of companies in real-time bidding auctions, hundreds of times per day, including to companies that never win the auction and have no legitimate business purpose receiving the data.<sup><a href="#fn3" id="ref3" style="text-decoration:none">[3]</a></sup></li>
<li>Surveillance pricing research shows that comprehensive behavioral tracking can extract 12.2% more profit through individual willingness-to-pay extraction, a mechanism invisible to consumers and impossible to detect or contest.<sup><a href="#fn4" id="ref4" style="text-decoration:none">[4]</a></sup></li>
<li>Government agencies have purchased commercial data broker databases to circumvent warrant requirements, acquiring location history, behavioral profiles, and sensitive personal data without legal process.<sup><a href="#fn5" id="ref5" style="text-decoration:none">[5]</a></sup></li>
</ul></div>
</section>
<section class="bg-cream ruled" id="pil-reform">
<div class="wrap" style="margin-bottom:0"><h2 style="color:var(--accent-color)">Key Reform Areas</h2></div>
<div class="wrap"><div class="reform-grid">
<div class="reform-card"><h3>Data Broker Regulation</h3><p>Federal registration, centralized deletion, categorical prohibition on sensitive data, government procurement ban.</p></div>
<div class="reform-card"><h3>Ad-Tech and RTB Reform</h3><p>Data minimization in real-time bidding, ban on behavioral targeting of prohibited categories, prohibition on targeting minors, political advertising transparency.</p></div>
<div class="reform-card"><h3>Behavioral Modification</h3><p>Dark patterns prohibition, engagement optimization limits, psychographic profiling ban, categorical protections for minors.</p></div>
<div class="reform-card"><h3>Surveillance Pricing</h3><p>Core pricing prohibition, data broker pipeline ban, transparency and disclosure, private right of action.</p></div>
<div class="reform-card"><h3>Algorithmic Discrimination</h3><p>FCRA extension to all consequential decisions, algorithmic impact assessments, adverse action notice rights, protected class proxy prohibition.</p></div>
<div class="reform-card"><h3>Enforcement Architecture</h3><p>FTC and CFPB jurisdiction, state AG concurrent authority, private right of action, proactive audit mandate, escalating sanctions, whistleblower protections.</p></div>
</div></div>
