<!-- ── FAMILY: DBKR ── -->
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-dbkr">
<div class="family-header">
  <span class="family-code">PRIV</span>
  <span class="family-title">DBKR: Data Broker Regulation</span>
  <span class="family-count">0/6 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-DBKR-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-DBKR-0001</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Definition and Scope of Data Broker Activity</p>
<p class="rule-plain">A data broker is any company whose business is collecting and selling personal information about people who are not their direct customers. This rule defines what counts as a data broker and who must follow the rules in this family.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">A "data broker" is any commercial entity that collects, aggregates, processes, or sells personal data about individuals who are not in a direct commercial relationship with that entity at the time of collection. This definition includes: companies whose primary business is acquiring and reselling personal data; companies that collect personal data as a secondary business and monetize it through licensing, sale, or exchange; data analytics firms whose outputs incorporate or are derived from third-party personal data; identity resolution and data enrichment services; and credit reporting agencies not otherwise regulated under the Fair Credit Reporting Act with respect to their non-FCRA data practices. Entities acting solely as data processors on behalf of a data controller do not qualify as data brokers under this definition with respect to that processing relationship. Entities that are otherwise covered by this definition are not exempt due to partial FCRA coverage; FCRA-covered practices remain subject to FCRA, and non-FCRA practices are subject to this family. A natural person's data about themselves does not constitute data broker activity.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The definition follows the functional approach of the FTC's 2014 data broker report, which identified hundreds of companies operating in this space. The Christl and Spiekermann (2016) academic mapping identifies 10 data broker business models, most of which are covered by this definition. The FCRA carve-out is intentional: FCRA-regulated credit bureaus are also data brokers in their non-FCRA operations, and this gap has historically allowed Experian, TransUnion, and Equifax to sell marketing data without FCRA constraints. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0019 (definitions must be functional, not formal). Cross-reference: PRIV-DBKR-0002 (registration requirement).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-DBKR-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-DBKR-0002</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Federal Data Broker Registration</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Every data broker must register with the FTC and pay an annual fee. The FTC must publish a searchable public list of all registered brokers. Unregistered brokers may not operate.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Every entity meeting the definition of data broker in PRIV-DBKR-0001 must register annually with the Federal Trade Commission before conducting any data broker activity. Registration must include: the entity's legal name and all operating names; a description of data collection sources; a description of data product categories offered for sale or license; a disclosure of whether the entity sells or licenses data to government entities; a list of all data sharing partnerships with other data brokers or advertising technology platforms; and the identity of a designated privacy officer. The FTC must publish and maintain a searchable public registry of all registered data brokers within 180 days of the effective date of this rule. Operating as an unregistered data broker is a per-day violation subject to PRIV-ENFA-0001 enforcement. Successor entities following mergers or acquisitions must re-register within 90 days. New entrants must register before commencing operations.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">California's data broker registration law (AB 1202, 2019) is the only existing U.S. model; it requires registration with the California Privacy Protection Agency but provides no public directory and has minimal disclosure requirements. Federal registration with a public directory is the minimum infrastructure necessary for enforcement. The FTC's 2014 report found it could not even compile a complete list of data brokers operating in the U.S. That structural opacity is itself the first enforcement problem to solve. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0011 (regulated entities must be identifiable). Cross-reference: PRIV-DBKR-0003 (deletion mechanism).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-DBKR-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-DBKR-0003</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Centralized Consumer Deletion Mechanism</p>
<p class="rule-plain">You should be able to request deletion of your personal data from all data brokers through a single government-run portal, not hundreds of separate requests to hundreds of companies.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The FTC must establish and operate a centralized consumer deletion portal through which any individual may submit a single deletion request covering all registered data brokers. Upon receiving a valid request, each registered data broker must delete all personal data held about the requesting individual within 30 days, confirm deletion to the FTC portal, and cease re-acquiring data about that individual from third-party sources for 12 months following the deletion. Data brokers may not charge individuals for exercising deletion rights. Data brokers may not require individuals to create accounts with the data broker as a condition of exercising deletion rights. Deletion is permanent with respect to the data deleted; data brokers may reacquire data after the 12-month suppression window expires only if new collection satisfies the purpose limitation in PRIV-DBKR-0005. Brokers must delete data across all downstream licensees and report downstream deletion compliance to the FTC portal within 60 days.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The no-account requirement closes a loophole in which brokers required consumers to create accounts (and thereby provide more data) to exercise deletion rights. The 12-month suppression window prevents immediate re-acquisition that would nullify deletion. The downstream deletion requirement is novel but necessary: a deletion right that does not follow data through the supply chain is an empty right. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0014 (rights must be practically exercisable, not nominally available). Cross-reference: PRIV-DBKR-0002 (registration basis for portal operation).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-DBKR-0004">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-DBKR-0004</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Categorical Prohibition on Sensitive Data</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Some types of personal information are too sensitive to be collected and sold, period, no matter what you signed. Location history, health data, and behavioral vulnerability scores are among the categories that may not be bought and sold.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">No data broker may collect, hold, license, sell, or transfer any of the following categories of personal data: (a) Precise location history: any record of a person's physical location at a precision of 100 meters or finer, maintained for more than 24 hours; (b) Inferred or disclosed health and medical information, including disability status, mental health history, substance use, and medication history; (c) Reproductive health information, including pregnancy, contraception use, abortion history, and fertility treatment; (d) Behavioral vulnerability scores: any model output predicting susceptibility to addiction, compulsive behavior, debt distress, emotional manipulation, or psychological distress; (e) Immigration or citizenship status; (f) Biometric identifiers, including facial geometry, voiceprint, gait, and genetic data; (g) Inferred political affiliation, party registration, voting history, or political contribution records not otherwise in the public record. No consent, contract, or terms-of-service provision may waive or contract around these prohibitions. The foregoing list is a floor; the FTC may designate additional categories by rulemaking.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The categorical approach follows the CPRA sensitive data framework but extends it to data brokers and strips the consent exception. The consent exception was deliberately excluded based on the academic evidence (Acquisti, Brandimarte, and Loewenstein 2015) that consent to data practices is not meaningfully informed or voluntary at scale; sensitive data requires categorical prohibition, not an opt-out right. The behavioral vulnerability score prohibition targets the most commercially valuable and most harmful data broker product: the identification of psychologically exploitable individuals for targeted advertising and lending. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0009 (high-harm categories require categorical prohibition, not procedural protection). Cross-reference: PRIV-BMOD-0003 (psychographic profiling prohibition).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-DBKR-0005">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-DBKR-0005</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Data Minimization and Purpose Limitation</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Data brokers may only collect personal data that is necessary for a specific, stated purpose, and may only use it for that purpose. Collecting everything and figuring out what to do with it later is prohibited.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">A registered data broker may collect and hold personal data only for a specific, documented, and lawful purpose. The stated purpose must be disclosed at registration and updated within 30 days of any change. Data brokers may not hold personal data in excess of what is necessary and proportionate to the stated purpose. Data must be deleted when it is no longer needed for the stated purpose, and in no case may it be held for more than three years without a demonstrated ongoing business necessity. Secondary use for a new purpose requires either: (a) a new affirmative consent that specifically identifies the new purpose; or (b) a finding that the secondary use is strictly compatible with the original purpose under a FTC compatibility test. "Strictly compatible" does not include any commercial use not contemplated in the original purpose. Cross-sale or cross-license to another data broker constitutes a new use requiring separate justification.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Purpose limitation is the structural principle that most fundamentally constrains data broker operations. The compatibility test is modeled on Article 5(1)(b) of GDPR. The three-year maximum holding period is derived from the FTC's recommended retention limits in the 2014 report. The cross-sale provision is necessary because purpose limitation rules routinely fail when data can be transferred to a third party with a different stated purpose. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0015 (purpose limitation is a precondition for lawful collection, not an exception to it).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-DBKR-0006">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-DBKR-0006</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Prohibition on Government Procurement of Commercial Surveillance Data</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Government agencies may not buy data broker products to get around the warrant requirement. If acquiring the data directly would require a warrant, buying it from a data broker also requires a warrant.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">No federal, state, or local government agency may purchase, license, receive by gift, or otherwise acquire any personal data product from a registered data broker or any substantially similar commercial entity if: (a) acquisition of that data directly from the individual or from a communications provider would require a warrant, court order, or other legal process under the Fourth Amendment or any federal statute; or (b) the data product includes any of the prohibited categories in PRIV-DBKR-0004. Existing contracts with data brokers for data products covered by this prohibition are void ab initio with respect to future deliverables and must be terminated within 180 days. Law enforcement agencies with pending investigations may seek a judicial order authorizing specific, limited acquisition for a named investigation subject. The prohibition applies to intelligence community elements subject to Executive Order 12333 with respect to data about U.S. persons.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The Fourth Amendment's third-party doctrine (Smith v. Maryland, 1979; Carpenter v. United States, 2018) creates an ongoing loophole: data voluntarily shared with a service provider may be obtainable without a warrant. The 2024 report by the Office of the Director of National Intelligence confirmed that federal agencies were routinely purchasing commercially available information that would require legal process if sought directly. This rule closes the procurement loophole without eliminating legitimate law enforcement use through judicial process. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0009 (government may not launder constitutional rights violations through commercial intermediaries).</p>
</div>

</div><!-- /.rule-grid -->
</div><!-- /.policy-family fam-dbkr -->

<!-- ── FAMILY: ADTC ── -->
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-adtc">
<div class="family-header">
  <span class="family-code">PRIV</span>
  <span class="family-title">ADTC: Ad-Tech and Real-Time Bidding Reform</span>
  <span class="family-count">0/5 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-ADTC-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-ADTC-0001</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">RTB Bid Request Data Minimization</p>
<p class="rule-plain">When websites sell ad space in real-time auctions, they currently broadcast your personal profile to hundreds of companies that didn't win the auction and have no right to your data. This rule limits what can be shared in those auctions.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Any advertising technology platform, supply-side platform, demand-side platform, or data management platform participating in real-time bidding ad auctions may include in a bid request only: the broad content category of the page on which the ad will appear; the general geographic region of the user at a precision no finer than the metropolitan statistical area; the ad slot dimensions and technical requirements; a one-way hashed device identifier that cannot be linked back to a natural person without a key held exclusively by the originating publisher; and contextual signals directly related to the page content. Bid requests may not include behavioral profile data, third-party data broker segments, cross-site tracking identifiers, precise location data, inferred demographic attributes, or any identifier that enables cross-context behavioral tracking. All bid request data must be deleted by all losing bidders within one hour of the auction closing. Winning bidders may retain bid request data only for billing reconciliation and must delete it within 30 days.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The Irish Council for Civil Liberties (2022) documented that the average U.S. consumer's data is broadcast to 1,015 companies per day through RTB auctions. The GDPR's Article 5(1)(c) data minimization requirement has been applied to RTB by European data protection authorities; the Belgian DPA found the IAB's Transparency and Consent Framework (TCF) incompatible with GDPR in 2022. The one-hour deletion requirement follows the UK ICO's guidance on RTB. The cross-site tracking identifier prohibition is the operationally significant constraint: it targets the specific mechanism (third-party cookies and device fingerprinting) through which RTB creates persistent behavioral profiles. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0015 (minimize data transit, not just data storage).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-ADTC-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-ADTC-0002</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Ban on Behavioral Targeting Using Sensitive Data</p>
<p class="rule-plain">No advertiser may target you based on health information, location history, political beliefs, or the other sensitive categories listed in PRIV-DBKR-0004, even if you consented to a privacy policy.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">No advertising platform, service, or data broker may target, segment, or select advertising audiences on the basis of any data in the prohibited categories defined in PRIV-DBKR-0004, or on the basis of any behavioral inferences derived from those categories, regardless of whether the targeting is described as interest-based, contextual, or first-party. Advertisers may not purchase or use audience segments that are substantially derived from prohibited data categories, even if those segments are not labeled with the underlying source data. Platforms must audit all audience segments offered for sale to advertisers and certify to the FTC annually that no offered segment is derived from prohibited categories. Platforms that discover non-compliant segments must remove them within 30 days and report the discovery to the FTC.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The audit and certification requirement closes the primary evasion path: laundering sensitive data through multiple enrichment steps before selling it as a generic audience segment. "Substantially derived" means that the predictive value of the segment is primarily attributable to prohibited data; this is a functional test, not a formal one. The prohibition applies regardless of consent because PRIV-DBKR-0004's categorical prohibition on collecting sensitive data makes downstream advertising use of that data automatically non-compliant. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0009 (prohibitions must run through the supply chain, not only to the first-tier collector).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-ADTC-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-ADTC-0003</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Prohibition on Behavioral Targeting of Minors</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Children and teenagers may not be targeted with behavioral advertising, period. Platforms must treat any user they cannot verify as an adult as a minor for targeting purposes.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">No advertising platform, service, or data broker may engage in behavioral targeting of any individual under the age of 18 or any individual who is "reasonably inferable" as a minor. A minor is "reasonably inferable" when: the platform, service, or application is primarily directed at minors; the individual has disclosed their age as under 18 to the platform; the behavioral signals of the individual are consistent with a minor as established by FTC guidance; or the data was collected through a service that obtained parental consent under COPPA. The prohibition applies to all forms of behavioral advertising, including interest-based targeting, behavioral retargeting, lookalike audience expansion based on minor behavioral profiles, and psychographic targeting. Platforms with more than 100,000 U.S. minor users must designate a Chief Privacy Officer for minors and file an annual compliance report with the FTC.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">COPPA (1998) applies only to children under 13 on sites directed at children; it does not cover teenagers, does not cover sites not directed at children that happen to have minor users, and was designed for a pre-smartphone internet. The "reasonably inferable" standard is derived from the FTC's 2022 COPPA rulemaking proposal. The compliance officer requirement for large platforms is modeled on GDPR Article 37 (Data Protection Officer). PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0009 (categorical protection for minors; bright-line age thresholds are required for consistent enforcement).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-ADTC-0004">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-ADTC-0004</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Political Advertising Transparency Repository</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Every political ad on the internet must be archived in a public database that shows who paid for it, how much they paid, and what targeting was used, for at least four years.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Any platform that accepts payment for political advertising, issue advertising, or any communication that refers to a candidate, ballot measure, or political party must maintain a publicly accessible digital advertising archive containing: the full text and creative content of the ad; the name and contact information of the advertiser and any organization paying for the ad; the total amount paid and the dates of the campaign; the targeting parameters used, including the criteria, the data sources used to build targeting audiences, and the estimated size of the reached audience; and the number of impressions delivered by demographic category. This archive must be maintained for a minimum of four years from the date of the last impression and must be accessible through a machine-readable API. Platforms with more than 5 million U.S. monthly active users are subject to real-time reporting; smaller platforms are subject to quarterly batch reporting.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The Honest Ads Act (proposed multiple times, never passed) would have required similar disclosures for online political ads. The FEC's existing political ad disclosure rules (52 U.S.C. 30120) do not apply to most digital advertising. The targeting parameter disclosure is the operationally significant requirement: knowing that an ad existed is less important than knowing who was targeted and why. The API requirement ensures that researchers, journalists, and regulators can analyze patterns across campaigns and platforms. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0020 (democratic integrity requires transparency in political communication; targeting information is as important as content).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-ADTC-0005">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-ADTC-0005</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Contextual Advertising Safe Harbor</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Advertising based purely on the content of the page you're reading, with no personal profiling, is allowed. This rule creates a protected lane for privacy-respecting advertising so that restricting behavioral surveillance doesn't eliminate advertising as a business model.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Any advertising that is based solely on the content of the page on which the ad appears, the broad geographic region of the user at the metropolitan statistical area level or coarser, and general device type, without use of any cross-context behavioral tracking, personal profile data, or third-party audience segments, is per se compliant with PRIV-ADTC-0001 and PRIV-ADTC-0002 and does not require any additional consent or disclosure beyond standard ad labeling. Contextual advertising that uses proxy targeting to reach audiences that are functionally equivalent to audiences targeted on the basis of prohibited categories (for example, advertising predatory loans on pages about debt distress or addiction) does not qualify for the safe harbor and is subject to full enforcement under PRIV-ADTC-0002.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The safe harbor is economically significant because it preserves an advertising model that does not require surveillance infrastructure. Research by Trusona/Rau and others has found that contextual advertising achieves near-comparable conversion rates to behavioral advertising for most categories of advertisers. The proxy-exploitation carve-out closes the obvious evasion path: using "contextual" labels to target vulnerable populations (people reading about addiction, mental health, debt, or pregnancy) with exploitative products. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0022 (compliance paths must be clearly defined; prohibitions should not eliminate all lawful alternatives).</p>
</div>

</div><!-- /.rule-grid -->
</div><!-- /.policy-family fam-adtc -->

<!-- ── FAMILY: BMOD ── -->
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-bmod">
<div class="family-header">
  <span class="family-code">PRIV</span>
  <span class="family-title">BMOD: Behavioral Modification Prohibition</span>
  <span class="family-count">0/5 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-BMOD-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-BMOD-0001</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Dark Patterns Prohibition</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Companies may not use design tricks to make you do things you did not intend to do, like signing up for a subscription without realizing it, or making it easy to say yes and hard to say no.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">No commercial entity operating a digital interface (including websites, applications, and connected device interfaces) may deploy interface design that: obscures, delays, or creates unnecessary friction in the exercise of any legally protected consumer right including cancellation, deletion, or opt-out; uses visual hierarchy, contrast, or placement to make consent-granting options more prominent or easier to complete than refusal options; presents repeated requests to change a previously stated preference after that preference has been clearly expressed; uses misleading language, false urgency, or emotional manipulation in interface elements associated with commercial consent or refusal; or hides material terms, costs, or conditions in interface elements that are not prominently displayed and cannot be missed by a reasonable consumer. These prohibitions apply regardless of whether the interface design meets any existing technical accessibility standard.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The FTC's 2022 report on dark patterns (Bringing Dark Patterns to Light) documented over 75 specific techniques in use by major platforms, establishing that dark patterns are industrialized, not idiosyncratic; they require professional design expertise and shared practitioner vocabulary, meaning they are the product of deliberate design choices, not accidents. The IAB's own dark patterns taxonomy confirms that these are recognized professional practices. The prohibition does not require proof of harm in individual cases; the design itself constitutes the violation. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0014 (consent must be informed, voluntary, and specific; interface design that undermines those conditions is not neutral).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-BMOD-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-BMOD-0002</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Engagement Optimization Prohibition</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Platforms may not use algorithms specifically designed to keep you scrolling or clicking longer than you would otherwise, by exploiting psychological tendencies like variable reward schedules or fear of missing out.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">No platform with more than 1 million U.S. monthly active users may deploy engagement optimization systems that are designed to maximize time spent, session length, or interaction frequency through mechanisms that exploit psychological vulnerabilities rather than deliver genuine utility. Prohibited mechanisms include: variable reward schedules designed to create compulsive checking behavior; artificial social validation signals (likes, engagement counts, follower counts) deployed to exploit social comparison vulnerabilities; notification systems designed to generate anxiety about missed content rather than to deliver user-requested information; and feed ranking systems that weight content based on its capacity to generate negative emotional arousal, outrage, or fear. Platforms must make available an engagement-neutral feed option that ranks content chronologically or by user-specified criteria without algorithmic amplification for emotional arousal.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Montag and Diefenbach (2018) established the neurological basis for variable reinforcement schedule effects in social media design. Twenge et al. (2018) documented the correlation between social media use and adolescent depression. Haugen (2021) whistleblower disclosures confirmed that internal Meta research showed Instagram worsened body image issues for teenage girls; this research was suppressed. The engagement-neutral feed requirement provides a concrete compliance pathway that does not require platforms to exit advertising-based business models. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0009 (prohibition applies to the design mechanism, not the outcome; intent to exploit is established by the design choice, not individual harm).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-BMOD-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-BMOD-0003</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Psychographic Profiling for Persuasion Purposes</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Companies may not build psychological profiles of you and use those profiles to personalize persuasion, including advertising and political messaging, in ways designed to exploit your specific emotional vulnerabilities.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">No commercial entity may construct or use psychographic profiles (predictive models of individual psychological traits, emotional states, vulnerabilities, personality dimensions, or behavioral tendencies derived from behavioral data) for purposes of personalized persuasion, including advertising targeting, political messaging, or recommendation system weighting. A psychographic profile is covered by this prohibition if it predicts susceptibility to specific emotional appeals, identifies psychological vulnerabilities for exploitation, models personality dimensions for message personalization, or estimates individual resistance to refusal. The prohibition applies regardless of whether the profile is constructed internally or purchased from a third party. Predictive models used in professional clinical settings under applicable licensure and with patient consent are exempt.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The Cambridge Analytica disclosure (2018) established that psychographic profiling for political persuasion purposes was an industrialized commercial practice, not a novel research project; Facebook's own research (Kramer et al. 2014) established that emotional contagion manipulation through content selection is experimentally validated and deployed at scale. The clinical exemption is narrow: it covers only licensed providers in direct treatment relationships with consenting patients. The prohibition applies to the construction and use of the profile for persuasion; it does not prohibit all behavioral modeling. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0009 (psychological manipulation of individuals without consent is a categorical harm, not a calibrated risk).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-BMOD-0004">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-BMOD-0004</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Minors: Categorical Engagement Prohibition</p>
<p class="rule-plain">For users under 18, all engagement optimization features are prohibited entirely, not just regulated. Platforms must default to chronological feeds and basic notification controls for minor users.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">For any platform user who is under 18 or who is "reasonably inferable" as a minor under the standard in PRIV-ADTC-0003: all engagement optimization features as defined in PRIV-BMOD-0002 are categorically prohibited; the default feed must be chronological or user-specified, with algorithmic ranking available only as an explicit opt-in by the user's parent or guardian; push notification systems for minor users must be configurable by parents or guardians and must default to off between 10 p.m. and 7 a.m. local time; and no feature designed to generate social comparison, social anxiety, or fear of missing out may be displayed to minor users, including public like counts, public follower counts, and streak counters. Platforms with more than 50,000 U.S. minor users must file annual compliance reports with the FTC documenting engagement architecture for minor accounts.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The categorical prohibition for minors is justified by the developmental psychology literature establishing that adolescents are uniquely susceptible to social comparison mechanisms and variable reinforcement; the harm is not speculative. The 10 p.m. to 7 a.m. notification default reflects sleep health research (Twenge and Campbell 2019) documenting the sleep disruption effects of nighttime social media use. The opt-in architecture for parental override is calibrated to the age-specific developmental risk while preserving parental autonomy. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0009 (categorical protection for developmentally vulnerable populations is required where calibrated harm prevention is demonstrably inadequate).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-BMOD-0005">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-BMOD-0005</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Third-Party Behavioral Modification Service Liability</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Companies that provide the tools platforms use to manipulate user behavior are jointly liable with the platforms that deploy them. The suppliers of dark pattern toolkits are not off the hook.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Any third-party service provider that offers, licenses, or deploys behavioral modification tools, engagement optimization systems, psychographic profiling services, or dark pattern toolkits to platform operators is jointly and severally liable with the platform operator for violations of PRIV-BMOD-0001 through PRIV-BMOD-0004 attributable to those tools or systems. "Jointly and severally liable" means that the FTC or any private plaintiff may bring an enforcement action against either the platform operator or the third-party service provider, or both, for the full amount of applicable penalties. Third-party service providers that audit their products for compliance with PRIV-BMOD-0001 through PRIV-BMOD-0003 and certify compliance to the FTC annually may assert an affirmative defense of good-faith compliance in any enforcement action.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Joint liability for third-party service providers is the mechanism that prevents outsourcing of prohibited conduct. Platforms that could not lawfully operate the engagement optimization system themselves cannot purchase that system from a vendor and thereby avoid liability. The certification affirmative defense creates an incentive for third-party providers to proactively audit their products, converting potential adversaries into compliance partners. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0009 (prohibitions must reach the full supply chain; first-tier liability only creates evasion through vertical disaggregation).</p>
</div>

</div><!-- /.rule-grid -->
</div><!-- /.policy-family fam-bmod -->

<!-- ── FAMILY: SVPR ── -->
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-svpr">
<div class="family-header">
  <span class="family-code">PRIV</span>
  <span class="family-title">SVPR: Surveillance Pricing Prohibition</span>
  <span class="family-count">0/7 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-SVPR-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-SVPR-0001</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Definitions and Scope</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Surveillance pricing is when a company uses your personal data to figure out the most you would pay for something, and then charges you exactly that. This rule defines the practice and establishes what it covers.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">"Surveillance pricing" means the use of any personal data profile, whether assembled by data brokers, platform behavioral tracking, purchase history, location data, device fingerprints, credit data, inferred psychological attributes, or any combination, to set, adjust, confirm, or personalize a price for a specific individual above the price that individual would have been charged without the profiling. The definition is technology-neutral and applies regardless of whether the price differentiation is described as personalization, dynamic pricing, loyalty pricing, willingness-to-pay optimization, or any other commercial term. "Price" includes any monetary charge, fee, subscription rate, insurance premium, loan interest rate, security deposit, rental rate, or any other form of financial consideration. The definition covers both real-time price adjustment and the routing of individuals into pricing tiers on the basis of their behavioral profiles.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The technology-neutral definition is required by PLOS-KERN-0022 (systems must adapt to technological change without crisis overhaul). Cross-reference: PRIV-DBKR-0004 (categorical prohibition on behavioral vulnerability scores); PRIV-SVPR-0003 (data broker pipeline ban). The FTC launched an investigation of eight surveillance pricing firms in January 2025; the report was subsequently removed from the FTC website. The Shiller (2020) paper establishing the 12.2% profit extraction finding is the primary academic reference establishing surveillance pricing as a quantified harm, not a theoretical concern.</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-SVPR-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-SVPR-0002</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Core Prohibition</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Using your personal data profile to charge you more than others pay for the same thing is illegal. Companies may offer loyalty discounts based on your relationship with them, but may not use your psychological profile to extract the maximum you will pay.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">No commercial entity may engage in surveillance pricing as defined in PRIV-SVPR-0001. This prohibition applies to any transaction with an individual consumer in the United States regardless of where the commercial entity is domiciled. Pricing based on a direct, continuous, and transparent commercial relationship with a specific consumer (such as loyalty program pricing, length-of-relationship discounts, or volume discounts for established customers) is permitted if: the pricing criteria are disclosed to the consumer; the criteria are based solely on the nature of the direct commercial relationship, not on third-party data profiles; and the criteria do not incorporate any prohibited data category from PRIV-DBKR-0004. Market-level dynamic pricing (such as airline seat pricing that changes based on aggregate demand, not individual profiles) is permitted if it does not use individual behavioral data to set individual prices.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The distinction between relationship-based pricing and profile-based pricing is the operationally critical line in this family. A loyalty discount based on being a ten-year customer is a product of the commercial relationship. A price adjustment based on a behavioral vulnerability score purchased from a data broker is an extraction of economic surplus from an individual identified as unable or unlikely to resist. The market-level dynamic pricing carve-out preserves commodity-market price discovery while prohibiting individual-level surplus extraction. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0017 (where a sector exhibits market concentration sufficient to deny consumers the practical ability to refuse, negotiate, or exit, rule design must include structural remedies).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-SVPR-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-SVPR-0003</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Data Broker Pipeline Prohibition</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Data brokers may not build or sell pricing profile products. Selling a company a profile of your willingness to pay is itself prohibited, not just using that profile to set prices.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">No registered data broker or substantially similar commercial entity may assemble, hold, license, sell, or transfer any data product that: is specifically designed or marketed for use in individual price setting; includes individual willingness-to-pay estimates, financial distress indicators, or behavioral vulnerability scores for pricing purposes; or enables the identification of individuals by their capacity to pay a price above a population average for a given product or service. Violations are joint and several with any retail or service entity that purchases and deploys such profiles in violation of PRIV-SVPR-0002.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The joint-and-several liability provision follows the BMOD third-party liability model (PRIV-BMOD-0005). A prohibition on using surveillance pricing that does not also prohibit the data broker supply chain for surveillance pricing products is a prohibition on deployment but not on the market infrastructure. Without supply-side prohibition, the downstream prohibition creates an information asymmetry in enforcement (regulators must detect individual pricing violations rather than auditing known product categories at the source). PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0009 (prohibitions must run through the full supply chain).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-SVPR-0004">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-SVPR-0004</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Permitted Pricing Practices</p>
<p class="rule-plain">This rule protects legitimate pricing practices, including discounts, sales, and market-based dynamic pricing, so the prohibition on surveillance pricing does not disrupt ordinary commerce.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The following pricing practices are explicitly permitted under this family and are not subject to PRIV-SVPR-0002: (a) publicly announced promotional pricing available to all consumers; (b) geographic pricing differentials based on cost of service delivery, taxation, or regulatory requirements, provided the basis is disclosed; (c) pricing that varies based on the consumer's membership in a class defined by direct relationship criteria (employees, students, veterans, or members), provided the class criteria are disclosed and do not incorporate prohibited data categories; (d) market-level dynamic pricing based on aggregate supply and demand without individual behavioral profiling; and (e) pricing negotiation between parties of comparable bargaining power in commercial, not consumer, transactions.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The affirmative permitted practices list is required to prevent enforcement overreach and business uncertainty. The geographic pricing carve-out reflects legitimate cost differences. The class membership carve-out preserves group discounts while prohibiting the use of data broker profiles to sort individuals. The commercial-versus-consumer distinction at subsection (e) is important: surveillance pricing is most harmful in consumer transactions where the individual lacks market power to negotiate or verify the price they have been assigned. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0022 (lawful alternatives must be clearly specified).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-SVPR-0005">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-SVPR-0005</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Transparency and Disclosure</p>
<p class="rule-plain">If a company charges you a personalized price, you have the right to know that it happened, what data was used, and what the non-personalized price would have been.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Any commercial entity that engages in any form of individualized pricing (including permitted relationship-based pricing under PRIV-SVPR-0004) must: disclose to the consumer at the time of transaction that individualized pricing is in use; identify the categories of data used to determine the individualized price upon consumer request; and provide upon request the non-individualized market price for the same product or service. Disclosure must be in plain language and must be prominently displayed at the point of purchase, not buried in terms of service or privacy policies. A commercial entity that believes disclosure would reveal proprietary pricing algorithms may apply to the FTC for a confidential reporting exemption; the FTC may grant such exemption only if it finds that the pricing practice is fully compliant with PRIV-SVPR-0002.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The transparency requirement serves an enforcement function independent of the disclosure right: if consumers cannot identify that they are being subject to surveillance pricing, they cannot exercise their rights or report violations. The non-individualized price disclosure is the operationally significant requirement; it enables consumers to verify whether they are being charged above market. The proprietary algorithm exemption is a narrow safety valve for genuinely complex legitimate pricing models, with the FTC review ensuring it is not used to shield prohibited practices. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0020 (transparency is a precondition for the exercise of rights, not a substitute for them).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-SVPR-0006">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-SVPR-0006</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Enforcement Authority</p>
<p class="rule-plain">The FTC and state attorneys general can investigate and fine companies that use surveillance pricing. Financial sector surveillance pricing also falls under CFPB enforcement.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The Federal Trade Commission has primary enforcement authority over violations of PRIV-SVPR-0002 through PRIV-SVPR-0005 under this rule's authorization and under Section 5 of the FTC Act. The Consumer Financial Protection Bureau has concurrent enforcement authority over surveillance pricing in credit, insurance, and banking transactions. State attorneys general may bring enforcement actions under this family for violations affecting residents of their states. Enforcement is concurrent; a state action does not preclude a federal action, and a federal action does not preempt a state action, provided that the total civil penalty assessed does not exceed the statutory maximum for the most serious applicable violation. The FTC may promulgate rules implementing this family under its rulemaking authority without requiring separate congressional authorization.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The concurrent enforcement structure is derived from the FTC-CFPB coordination model established in the Dodd-Frank Act. Financial sector surveillance pricing (insurance, credit, lending) is the highest-harm application and requires CFPB expertise. The rulemaking authority clarification is necessary because the current FTC Magnuson-Moss rulemaking process is so slow (averaging seven or more years) that it cannot respond to rapidly evolving algorithmic practices. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-ENFA-0001 (enforcement authority must be specifically assigned; concurrent jurisdiction requires explicit non-preemption language).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-SVPR-0007">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-SVPR-0007</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Private Right of Action</p>
<p class="rule-plain">You can sue a company that used surveillance pricing against you. You don't have to wait for the government to act on your behalf.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Any individual who is subject to surveillance pricing in violation of PRIV-SVPR-0002 may bring a civil action in any court of competent jurisdiction against the violating entity and any data broker whose product was used in the violation. Statutory damages are $500 per violation for non-willful violations and $1,500 per violation for willful violations; "per violation" means per transaction in which prohibited surveillance pricing was applied to the individual. Actual damages may be sought in lieu of statutory damages. Class actions are permitted. The court may award attorneys' fees and costs to prevailing plaintiffs. Actions must be filed within four years of the later of the date the violation occurred or the date the plaintiff knew or reasonably should have known of the violation. The filing of a government enforcement action does not stay a pending private action.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The statutory damages model follows the Telephone Consumer Protection Act (47 U.S.C. 227), which has been effective in generating private enforcement even in cases where individual harm is difficult to quantify. The data broker joint liability in private actions is the supply-side deterrence mechanism: it creates financial risk for data brokers who supply surveillance pricing products even when the downstream retailer is the nominal violator. The four-year statute of limitations is extended relative to typical contract limitations because surveillance pricing is typically undetectable at the time of the violation. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-ENFA-0003 (private rights of action are required when individual violations are widespread but individually small).</p>
</div>

</div><!-- /.rule-grid -->
</div><!-- /.policy-family fam-svpr -->

<!-- ── FAMILY: ALGO ── -->
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-algo">
<div class="family-header">
  <span class="family-code">PRIV</span>
  <span class="family-title">ALGO: Algorithmic Discrimination</span>
  <span class="family-count">0/5 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-ALGO-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-ALGO-0001</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">FCRA Extension to All Consequential Algorithmic Decisions</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Computer systems that make decisions about credit, employment, housing, or insurance must follow the same rules that apply to credit bureau reports, including your right to see the information, dispute errors, and know when you've been denied based on it.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Any algorithmic decision system that produces outputs used in credit, insurance, employment, housing, education, or licensing decisions is a "consumer reporting system" subject to all applicable provisions of the Fair Credit Reporting Act (15 U.S.C. 1681 et seq.) including: the requirement to provide consumers access to all information used in their profile upon request; the requirement to investigate and correct disputed information within 30 days; the requirement to provide adverse action notices that include the specific factors and data sources that contributed to the adverse outcome; and the prohibition on reporting information that is more than seven years old (or in the case of bankruptcy, more than ten years). The extension applies to any entity that assembles or evaluates information about individuals for use by third parties in consequential decisions, regardless of whether that entity describes itself as a credit reporting agency.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Most data brokers are not consumer reporting agencies because they sell to buyers who make their own decisions, not for the enumerated FCRA purposes. But the practical effect is identical: a behavioral risk score sold to an insurance company is functionally a consumer report. The CFPB's 2023 proposed interpretive guidance on FCRA and AI-based credit decisions takes a similar but narrower position. The seven-year reporting limit is constitutionally significant: the use of historical behavioral data to make present-day decisions about individuals is a form of punishment for past conduct that has no limiting principle without a temporal cutoff. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0009 (rights in consequential decision-making are not dependent on the mechanism of the decision).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-ALGO-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-ALGO-0002</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Mandatory Algorithmic Impact Assessments</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Before deploying a computer system that makes or recommends decisions affecting people's lives, companies and agencies must evaluate whether it discriminates or causes other harms, and they must share those evaluations with regulators.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Any commercial entity or government agency that deploys an algorithmic decision system in a consequential domain (as defined in PRIV-ALGO-0001) must conduct and file with the applicable regulator a pre-deployment Algorithmic Impact Assessment (AIA) containing: a description of the system's purpose, inputs, and outputs; an analysis of the system's disparate impact on each protected class under Title VII, the Equal Credit Opportunity Act, the Fair Housing Act, and the Age Discrimination in Employment Act; an analysis of the data sources used, including whether any source is a data broker product or contains information derived from PRIV-DBKR-0004 prohibited categories; a description of the system's accuracy, error rate, and error distribution across demographic groups; and a mitigation plan for any identified disparate impacts. AIAs must be updated and refiled when the system is materially changed. AIAs are public records except for genuinely proprietary technical specifications, which must be filed under seal with the regulator.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The EU AI Act (2024) requires conformity assessments for high-risk AI systems in credit, employment, and education. The UK's ICO and Equality and Human Rights Commission have issued joint guidance on AI and equality law. No equivalent U.S. federal requirement exists. The public record requirement (with a narrow proprietary exception) is necessary for civil society and academic oversight; the regulator-only filing model has historically been captured by the industries it oversees. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0011 (regulated systems must be auditable; audit results must be publicly available except where specific and justified confidentiality applies).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-ALGO-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-ALGO-0003</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Adverse Action Notice and Explanation Rights</p>
<p class="rule-plain">If a computer system denies you credit, a job, housing, or insurance, you have the right to a plain-language explanation of why, what data was used, and how to dispute it. "A computer made the decision" is not a sufficient explanation.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Any entity that takes an adverse action against an individual on the basis of an algorithmic decision system in a consequential domain must provide the individual with a written adverse action notice that: identifies the specific system used; describes the primary factors that contributed to the adverse outcome in plain language at or below an 8th-grade reading level; identifies all data sources used, including any data broker products; discloses any data that was derived from PRIV-DBKR-0004 prohibited categories or from a sensitive attribute that was used as a proxy for a prohibited category; and provides a specific explanation of how each identified factor affected the outcome. The notice must include instructions for disputing incorrect information, the name and contact information of the entity responsible for the system, and the regulator to whom complaints may be directed. Notices that rely on proprietary algorithm confidentiality to withhold explanatory information are not compliant.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The existing FCRA adverse action notice (15 U.S.C. 1681m) requires disclosure of the credit reporting agency and score, but does not require disclosure of the factors driving the score when an algorithmic system not classified as a credit reporting agency is used. The CFPB's 2023 guidance states that "black box" algorithms cannot satisfy the adverse action notice requirement, but this is an interpretation, not a rule, and has been subject to challenge. The 8th-grade reading level requirement follows the plain language standard in PRIV-DBKR-0003. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0014 (the right to contest a decision requires knowing the basis for the decision; explanation is a precondition for due process, not a procedural nicety).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-ALGO-0004">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-ALGO-0004</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Prohibition on Protected Class Proxies</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Algorithmic systems may not use data that effectively predicts a person's race, sex, religion, or other protected characteristic as a substitute for using that characteristic directly. If it produces the same discrimination, it is illegal regardless of the label on the input.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">No algorithmic decision system subject to this family may use any input variable whose primary predictive value with respect to consequential outcomes is substantially attributable to its correlation with a protected class under applicable civil rights law, including race, color, national origin, sex, religion, disability, age, familial status, or sexual orientation. Third-party behavioral scores or data broker products whose predictive value is primarily derived from protected class membership are prohibited inputs regardless of how they are labeled. An entity that uses a facially neutral input variable that produces disparate impact outcomes substantially equal to those that would be produced by direct use of a protected characteristic bears the burden of demonstrating that the variable has independent predictive value not reducible to protected class correlation and that no less discriminatory alternative is reasonably available.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The proxy discrimination theory is established in fair lending law through the disparate impact standard (Griggs v. Duke Power Co., 1971; Texas Department of Housing and Community Affairs v. Inclusive Communities Project, 2015). The CFPB and HUD have both applied disparate impact analysis to algorithmic credit and housing decisions. The burden-shifting framework (entity must demonstrate independent predictive value) follows the Wards Cove Packing / EEOC burden structure and the burden allocation framework in PLOS-KERN-0009. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-KERN-0009 (disparate impact is a cognizable harm regardless of discriminatory intent; the burden of justification falls on the entity deploying the system).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-ALGO-0005">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-ALGO-0005</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Algorithmic Discrimination Private Right of Action</p>
<p class="rule-plain">If an algorithm discriminated against you in a consequential decision, you can sue in federal court. You do not have to file with an agency first.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Any individual who is subjected to algorithmic discrimination in violation of PRIV-ALGO-0004, or who is denied their rights under PRIV-ALGO-0001 through PRIV-ALGO-0003, may bring a civil action in any federal court of competent jurisdiction against: the entity that deployed the algorithmic decision system; any data broker whose product was used as an input to the system in violation of this family; and any third-party model developer whose system produced discriminatory outputs in violation of PRIV-ALGO-0004. Statutory damages are $500 to $5,000 per violation, with the amount set by the trier of fact based on the severity of the harm. Actual damages may be sought in lieu of or in addition to statutory damages. Equitable relief, including injunction and correction of records, is available. Class actions are permitted. Prevailing plaintiffs are entitled to attorneys' fees. Actions under this provision are not required to exhaust administrative remedies before filing.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The no-exhaustion requirement is critical; current civil rights enforcement requires administrative exhaustion (EEOC charge filing in employment discrimination) that can take years before a plaintiff reaches federal court. Algorithmic discrimination cases are often time-sensitive (credit, housing) and the administrative exhaustion requirement has historically been used to delay and exhaust plaintiffs. The third-party model developer liability closes the supply chain, consistent with PRIV-BMOD-0005 and PRIV-SVPR-0007. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-ENFA-0003 (private rights of action without exhaustion are required when administrative remedies are inadequate in speed and scope to the harm).</p>
</div>

</div><!-- /.rule-grid -->
</div><!-- /.policy-family fam-algo -->

<!-- ── FAMILY: ENFA ── -->
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-enfa">
<div class="family-header">
  <span class="family-code">PRIV</span>
  <span class="family-title">ENFA: Enforcement Architecture</span>
  <span class="family-count">0/6 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-ENFA-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-ENFA-0001</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">FTC and CFPB Jurisdiction and Lane Assignments</p>
<p class="rule-plain">The FTC enforces data broker, ad-tech, behavioral modification, and surveillance pricing rules. The CFPB handles financial sector data privacy. Both agencies have full civil penalty authority.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The Federal Trade Commission has primary enforcement jurisdiction over violations of PRIV-DBKR, PRIV-ADTC, PRIV-BMOD, and PRIV-SVPR, and over violations of PRIV-ALGO-0001 through PRIV-ALGO-0005 outside the credit, insurance, and banking sectors. The Consumer Financial Protection Bureau has primary enforcement jurisdiction over violations of PRIV-ALGO-0001 through PRIV-ALGO-0005 in the credit, insurance, lending, deposit account, and financial services sectors. Civil penalties under FTC enforcement are $50,000 per day per violation for first offenses and $100,000 per day per violation for repeat offenses, adjusted annually for inflation. Civil penalties under CFPB enforcement follow the Dodd-Frank Act tiered penalty structure. The FTC Act common carrier exemption does not apply to entities subject to this pillar; telecommunications carriers and their data broker subsidiaries are subject to FTC enforcement under this authorization.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The FTC Act common carrier exemption has historically prevented FTC enforcement against telephone and broadband companies; Congress has repeatedly declined to close this gap despite FTC requests. The CFPB lane assignment reflects the CFPB's existing expertise in algorithmic credit discrimination under the Equal Credit Opportunity Act. The $50,000 per day per violation penalty level is derived from the CAN-SPAM Act and COPPA civil penalty schedules, adjusted to reflect the scale of modern data operations. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-ENFA-0001 (enforcement jurisdiction must be explicitly assigned with clear lane assignments to prevent enforcement gaps caused by jurisdictional disputes).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-ENFA-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-ENFA-0002</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">State Attorney General Concurrent Authority</p>
<p class="rule-plain">State attorneys general can enforce these rules for residents of their state. States with stronger privacy laws can keep them. A federal floor does not eliminate stronger state protections.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The attorney general of any state, or the equivalent state official responsible for consumer protection enforcement, may bring a civil enforcement action in any court of competent jurisdiction against any entity that violates any provision of this pillar with respect to residents of that state. State enforcement is concurrent with federal enforcement. This pillar does not preempt any state law that provides greater protection for consumers, including the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA), California Privacy Rights Act (CPRA), and any state law enacted after the effective date of this pillar, except to the extent that a specific provision of state law is irreconcilably in conflict with a specific prohibition in this pillar. The burden of demonstrating irreconcilable conflict rests on the party seeking preemption. This pillar establishes a floor, not a ceiling, for consumer data protection in the United States.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Industry has consistently sought federal preemption of state privacy laws (including CCPA and CPRA) as part of any federal privacy framework. Federal preemption of CCPA would reduce, not increase, consumer protection in California, which has the most comprehensive currently operative state framework. The explicit non-preemption language and floor-not-ceiling declaration are required to prevent the federal law from being used as a weapon against state innovation. The irreconcilable-conflict standard follows the federal preemption doctrine in Altria Group v. Good (2008) and requires a genuinely incompatible command, not merely overlapping or more demanding requirements. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-FEDR-0003 (federal minimums do not displace state maximums).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-ENFA-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-ENFA-0003</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Private Right of Action with Statutory Damages</p>
<p class="rule-plain">You can sue companies that violate your data rights. You do not need to prove you were personally harmed in a way courts can quantify, because most data rights violations cause diffuse, hard-to-measure harm.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Any individual whose rights under this pillar are violated may bring a civil action in any federal or state court of competent jurisdiction. Statutory damages are available without proof of actual harm in the following amounts: $500 per violation for non-willful violations of PRIV-DBKR-0001 through PRIV-DBKR-0005; $1,000 per violation for willful violations of PRIV-DBKR or PRIV-ADTC; $2,500 per violation for violations of PRIV-BMOD-0001 through PRIV-BMOD-0004; $5,000 per violation for violations of PRIV-DBKR-0004 (prohibited categories) or PRIV-BMOD-0003 (psychographic profiling); and $500 to $5,000 per violation for algorithmic discrimination under PRIV-ALGO, with the amount determined by the court. Class actions are explicitly permitted. Courts may award equitable relief, injunctions, attorneys' fees, and costs. Statutory damages in class actions are subject to the discretion of the court to prevent awards that are disproportionate to the nature of the violation.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The statutory damages model without proof of actual harm is the most important structural feature: data privacy violations rarely produce individually measurable economic harm, but produce massive aggregate harm. The TCPA (47 U.S.C. 227) statutory damages model has demonstrated that per-violation statutory damages generate private enforcement even when individual harm is negligible. The higher per-violation amounts for PRIV-DBKR-0004 and PRIV-BMOD-0003 reflect the severity of sensitive data violations and psychographic manipulation. The class action court discretion provision is a safety valve against TCPA-style annihilatory class actions that courts have sometimes had to reduce. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-ENFA-0003 (private rights of action are required when violations are widespread, individually small, and inadequately deterred by agency enforcement alone).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-ENFA-0004">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-ENFA-0004</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Proactive Audit Mandate</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Regulators must actively look for violations; they cannot only respond to consumer complaints. Large data brokers and platforms must undergo independent audits, and the results must be public.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The FTC must conduct or commission proactive compliance audits of registered data brokers and covered platforms on the following schedule: any entity with annual revenues exceeding $1 billion derived from data activities must be audited annually; any entity with more than 10 million U.S. users or data subjects must be audited every two years; all other registered data brokers must be audited at least every five years. Audits must assess compliance with all families in this pillar and must include sampling of actual data products, bid request logs, pricing systems, and algorithmic decision outputs. Audit reports must be made public within 90 days of completion, with redactions limited to genuinely proprietary technical specifications. The FTC may contract with qualified independent auditors to fulfill this mandate; the cost of audits must be borne by the audited entity on a fee schedule established by the FTC.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Complaint-driven enforcement is structurally inadequate for data rights violations because: most violations are invisible to consumers; consumers who know they were violated often cannot prove it; and the economic incentive to violate is proportional to the scale of operation, meaning the largest violators face the weakest deterrence from individual complaint processing. The audit-cost-borne-by-entity model follows the banking examination fee structure (12 U.S.C. 1820) and the SEC examination model. The public report requirement converts audits from private negotiations into accountability mechanisms. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-ENFA-0004 (proactive enforcement is required when violations are structurally invisible to affected parties).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-ENFA-0005">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-ENFA-0005</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Escalating Sanctions and Structural Remedies</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Repeat violators face escalating fines, and the most serious violations can result in a company being required to delete all data it collected illegally, not just paying a fine. A fine you can absorb is not a deterrent.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">For entities that commit a second or subsequent violation of any provision of this pillar within five years of a prior violation: civil penalties are doubled for each successive violation up to a statutory maximum of $500,000 per day per violation; the FTC may impose enhanced compliance requirements including real-time monitoring, mandatory third-party audits, and management certification of compliance; and the FTC may seek disgorgement of all revenues attributable to the violating conduct. For violations of PRIV-DBKR-0004 (prohibited categories), PRIV-BMOD-0003 (psychographic profiling), or any violation found to be willful and systematic: the FTC may seek a structural remedy requiring the deletion of all data collected in violation of this pillar and a prohibition on reacquiring that data for five years; courts may order injunctive relief dissolving or restructuring a data broker found to be operating in systematic and willful violation of this pillar. Civil penalty revenue is deposited in a Data Rights Consumer Restitution Fund administered by the FTC for distribution to affected individuals.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The data-asset deletion remedy is the data sector equivalent of disgorgement of ill-gotten profits in securities enforcement: it removes the economic benefit of the violation (the data itself). Without deletion remedies, the optimal corporate strategy is to collect prohibited data, pay fines if caught, and keep the data. The Consumer Restitution Fund model follows the CFPB Civil Penalty Fund and the FTC redress fund models. Structural dissolution for systematic violations is an extreme remedy; it is calibrated to apply only to entities that have demonstrated a pattern of willful non-compliance that civil penalties have failed to deter. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-ENFA-0005 (sanctions must be sufficient to deter, not merely punish; for profitable systematic violations, structural remedies are required).</p>
</div>

<div class="policy-card status-proposed" id="PRIV-ENFA-0006">
<div class="rule-header">
  <code class="rule-id">PRIV-ENFA-0006</code>
  <span class="rule-badge">Proposed</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-status">🔵 Proposed</div>
<p class="rule-title">Whistleblower Protections</p>
<p class="rule-plain">Employees who report data privacy violations are protected from being fired or sued for reporting. Confidentiality agreements that try to prevent employees from reporting to regulators are unenforceable.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Any employee, contractor, or former employee who in good faith reports a violation of this pillar to the FTC, CFPB, a state attorney general, or any court of competent jurisdiction is protected from retaliation by any entity covered by this pillar. Prohibited retaliation includes termination, demotion, harassment, exclusion from business opportunities, and breach of confidentiality claims asserted to prevent good-faith reporting. Any confidentiality agreement, non-disclosure agreement, or arbitration provision that purports to prohibit or limit reporting to a regulator or court is void and unenforceable with respect to that prohibition. Whistleblowers who report violations that result in a final enforcement action recovering civil penalties of more than $1 million are entitled to an award of 10 to 30 percent of the civil penalties recovered, administered by the FTC. Retaliation claims may be brought in any federal or state court; prevailing plaintiffs are entitled to reinstatement, back pay, and attorneys' fees.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Data broker operations are opaque to external regulators; insider information is the most reliable source of evidence for systemic violations. The NDA carve-out is necessary because data companies routinely require employees to sign broad confidentiality agreements that purport to cover disclosure of company practices to regulators, a practice that, if enforceable, would eliminate the practical effect of whistleblower protections. The award structure follows the SEC whistleblower program (15 U.S.C. 78u-6), which has recovered more than $6 billion and paid more than $1.3 billion in awards since 2011. PolicyOS cross-reference: PLOS-ENFA-0006 (whistleblower protection is a structural enforcement mechanism, not an employment law nicety; NDAs that override it are void as against public policy).</p>
</div>

</div><!-- /.rule-grid -->
</div><!-- /.policy-family fam-enfa -->

</div><!-- /.wrap -->
