<section class="bg-dark on-dark ruled" id="pil-research">
<div class="wrap">
<p class="eyebrow">Research & Evidence</p>
<h2>The Evidence Base</h2>
<div class="research-body" style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.85)">
<p>McDonald and Cranor (2008) calculated that reading every privacy policy a consumer encounters would require 76 work days per year, establishing that notice-and-choice frameworks cannot provide meaningful informed consent at scale.<sup><a href="#fn2" style="text-decoration:none">[2]</a></sup> The Irish Council for Civil Liberties (2022) documented that the average American's behavioral profile is broadcast to more than 1,000 companies per day through real-time bidding auctions, including participants who never win the auction and therefore have no legitimate business purpose receiving the data.<sup><a href="#fn3" style="text-decoration:none">[3]</a></sup> Shiller (2020) demonstrated that comprehensive behavioral tracking enables 12.2% profit extraction through individual willingness-to-pay modeling, compared to 0.8% for demographic-only approaches, quantifying surveillance pricing as a measurable transfer from consumers to sellers rather than an efficiency gain.<sup><a href="#fn4" style="text-decoration:none">[4]</a></sup> A 2024 report by the Office of the Director of National Intelligence acknowledged that federal agencies were purchasing commercially available data about U.S. persons that would require legal process if sought directly, confirming that the data broker procurement loophole is not theoretical.<sup><a href="#fn5" style="text-decoration:none">[5]</a></sup> The FTC's January 2025 Surveillance Pricing Study examined eight companies using browsing history, GPS location, device fingerprints, social media data, and credit data for individual price setting. The Cambridge Analytica disclosure (2018) established that psychographic profiling for political persuasion purposes was an industrialized commercial practice; Meta's internal research (Kramer et al., 2014) established that emotional contagion through content selection is experimentally validated and deployed at scale.<sup><a href="#fn7" id="ref7" style="text-decoration:none">[7]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn6" id="ref6" style="text-decoration:none">[6]</a></sup></p>
</div>
</div>
</section>
